    "componentSelection": "Component IDs were selected based on the provided design system data and their suitability for the specified UI elements.  The `input` component was chosen for email and password fields due to its built-in validation capabilities.  The `button` component was used for its styling flexibility, and the `link` component was selected for its clear semantic meaning.",
    "styleApplication": "Styles were applied consistently across components to maintain visual harmony. The primary login button utilizes a distinct style to emphasize its role, while the social login buttons employ a secondary style to clearly distinguish them.  Text colors and primary colors for buttons are defined within the `styleInfo` property.",
    "designSystemMapping": "UI requirements were mapped directly to components within the design system.  Each component's properties and variants were selected based on the visual design and functional requirements, aligning with the design system's established naming conventions.",
    "variantDecisions": "Variants were chosen to provide the necessary functionality and visual cues. For example, the input fields utilize variants to specify input types, while the buttons use variants to distinguish primary and secondary actions.  These selections were made to enhance user experience and maintain visual consistency.",
    "nestedComponentHandling": "No nested components were detected in this design.  If nested structures were present, they would have been handled by using only single values for properties, omitting arrays to prevent potential conflicts.",
    "textPropertyMapping": "User-provided text content was mapped directly to the `text` property of each component, with no generic property names used. The design system's conventions for naming text properties within each component were strictly followed."
  }
}
